{"/service/ndnp/msar/batch_msar_lapis_ver01/data/sn85044791/00383345066/1958061901/0434.xml":{"full_text":"East Side\n-By P. D.\n3\nThe following was stolen from the San Francisco Chron\nicle and changed just enough to fit this locality.\n\"St. Peter faced two little old ladies who applied for\nadmission at the Pearly Gates. After asking all the pertinent\nquestions about saying their prayers, etc., he asked one lady\nwhere she lived; 'Cincinnati/ she said. 'Okey, you may go in\nAnd where are you from?' he asked the other lady,\n'Hattiesburg/ was the reply.\n'Well/ said St. Peter, 'you may go In, but you're not\ngoing to like it.'\"\nNo doubt you've heard the comment about the recession\nwhich has been attributed to Harry Truman, in which he\nis to have said: \"A recession is when the fellow next door is\nunemployed; a depression is when you're unemployed.\"\nSomeone told me about the comment by some fellow suf\nfering from what most of us suffer from the folks next\ndoor. Said the man: \"You know, everytime I catch up with\nthat fellow Jones next door he re-finances.\"\nThen Robert Spivack, the New York Post writer, whose\ncolumn \"Watch On The Potomac, I carry, told about the\nman who drove an old auto of some make up to the keeper\nof the toll bridge gate.\n\"Fifty cents,\" said the collector.\n\"Sold!\" exclaimed the driver.\nI'm sure there's nothing humorous about a recession,\nbut to me the whole thing was a surprise. I didn't know there\nhad ever been anything else.\nA note from Dr. L. T. Reid of Suffolk, Va. included a\ncard which I found amusing. It read: \"MY MIND IS ALREA\nDY MADE UP. DON'T CONFUSE ME WITH THE FACTS.\" While\nI have no idea as to who wrote that prose, I could name quite\na number who could have. But what's bad is the fact that\nI could name an even larger number who live in accordance\nwith the idea as it was expressed.\nSo many resolutions have been passed, as well as ulti\nmatums given, around our house until I can't keep count of\nthem. However, we have a new one, passed about the middle\nof May by me. In view of his having subscribed to this paper,\nI have issued orders that no one is to flip the TV dial on\nSunday while Steve Allen is on. A Steve Allen commercial\nor not, I don't care, Ed Sullivan is not a subscriber.\nOf course, I'm just name dropping. And that brings to\nmind a story told by a minister not long ago. Seems a mao\nwas about to pray. He began, \"God Next to him a voice\nsaid: \"Name dropper.\"\nAnyway, as I said to the mayor, \"Now, Iissen, Dick\nWhadda want? People are just people.\nThe 18th of July should be a happy day for some, and\nfor all, a pleasant day. It is then that The World Publishing\nCompany will bring out Harry Golden s book, ONLY. IN\nAMERICA. Harry is the Publisher, Editor, Feature Writer,\nGossip Columnist, Philosopher, etc. of THE CAROLINA ISRA\nELITE, published every now and then in Charlotte, N. C.\n(Three bucks a year, while I'm at it.)\nONLY IN AMERICA is Harry's first book,.which will con\ncontain a choice selection of his views on Heaven only\nknows how many and varied subjects. Harry has an idea on\n(Continued on Page 2)\nA Book\nReview\nBOLOGNA UNDER GLASS:\nTwenty-nine short stories, in two\nvolumes, by Steve Allen. \"The\nGirls on the 10th Floor\" (Holt,\n188 pp. $3.00) and ''Fourteen for\nTonight\" (Holt. 192 pp. $.00)\nIf you can imagine yourself\ngiving a dear friend companion\npictures of George and Martha\nWashington, in black walnut\nframes, these stories toy Steve\nAllen will leave you pold if not\nhelpless. On the other hand, if\nyou are more likely to give\nmatching slices of paper-4hin\nbologna, framed for mounting on\nthe wall of den or recreation\nroom, these books are just what\nyou need.\nThe great American public that\nclusters around the hot cathodes\nof TV every night knows Steve\nAllen very well. Also it may be\nremembered'that he starred tn the\nmovie on the life of Benny Good\nman, wrote \u201cBop Fables\u201d and\n\u201cThe Funny Man\u201d, and published\na volume of poetry called \u201cWry\non the Rocks\u201d.\nOne of these stories is about\na religious fanatic encountered on\nboard an airliner. At first the\nman recited uncomfortable pas\nsages from the Scriptures, and\ntried to give away religious tracts.\nNobody paid him much attention,\njust amused understanding as if\nhe had been a naughty, exasperat\ning child. Then he shouted that\nhe had a time bomb in his suit\ncase, set to go off in the baggage\ncompartment of the plane. He got\nplenty of attention but fast.\nThe pilot couldn\u2019t wait to get\ndown out of the sky before the\nthing went off, and it was a ter\nrifying experience for everybody.\nIf you have a friend who tra\nvels a lot by air, by all means\nsee that he reads \u201cThe Blood of\nthe Lamb\u2019\u2019. Then brace yourself\nagainst him in case he decides\nthat one good turn deserves an\nOh, yes, here is something else\nif you have a friend who has\nbeen slipping off to motels with\nsome other man\u2019s wife and you\nwant to let him know you know.\nIt is called \u201cDialogue\u201d and it\nis just the conversation that took\nplace, from the time they rode\noff together until the time they\nstarted back together. There is\nnot much philosophy in the story,\nbut one philosophical viewpoint\nis expressed:\n\u201cIt\u2019s a hypocritical world, my\nchesty wench; and the trouble\nisn\u2019t so much that everybody\u2019s\nwrong as it is that everybody\u2019s\nright.\u201d\nIn general the characters in the\nstories include mugs, movie stars,\nmissionaries, business men, pub\nlicity agents, lunatics, musicians,\netc. Steve Allen is a skilled ra\nconteur. He is at his best with\nsophisticated wit and irony. There\nis some depth, variety, and sensi\ntivity.\nLaughter of this kind ordinari\nly follows the collapse of some\ndiscipline or social restraint.\nThere was plenty of it in Eng\nland after 1660, following the\ndemise of the Puritan Common\nwealth, and the return of Charles\nII from France where he had been\nindulging in the arts of levity. The\ncomedy of the Restoration stage\nestablishes some kind of a high\n(Continued on Page 2)\nThe King Affair\u2014\nAn Expression Of Dishonest Intent\nBeing more or less subsidized\nby The Chronicle Star we have to\nget copy to the shop as far a\nhead as possible; therefore, as we\nwrite this, we don\u2019t know the\noutcome of the sanity hearing for\nProfessor Clennon King, the Neg\nro History professor formerly of\nAlcorn A&M College who at\ntempted to register for summer\nschool at the University of Mis\nsissippi on June 5th.\nExcept for degree, the sanity\nof Mr. King is of no great im\nportance. However, if he is de\nclared insane, the degree is of the\nutmost importance; and for a good\nreason.\nClennon King, we believe, mis\nrepresented his intention to the\npeople of the state and the na\ntion when he said he wanted to\nenter the University of Mississip\npi as a student. That was a com\nplete falsehood, we think.\nIn relating his actions and\nwords while on the campus we\nmust assume the press reports\nare true. (And who can doubt it?)\nNow, King was reported to have\nshouted \u201cHelp! Help!\u201d when he\nwasn\u2019t being bothered by anyone.\nAs a result he was taken to\nJackson by the Highway Patrol\nand it was decided to give him a\nsanity hearing.\nShould King be declared insane\nhe will have attained his goal\nwhich, we are convinced, was not\nto enroll as a student, but was\nto get a place on the faculty.\nAnd here it becomes of the ut\nmost importanct as to the degree\nof his insanity, and for this rea\nson:\nShould it be to a great enough\ndegree he just might be made a\nDean. Should it be to an even\ngreater degree, he could be made\nRegistar or be given some other\nadministrative post.\nIn any event, we hold that Pro\nfessor Clennon King expressed\ndishonest intent by saying he\nwanted to be a student. A man\nshould be honest about these\nthings. He should have just walk\non the campus at the University\nand said: \"I'm crazy as hell. I\nwant to teach school.\"\nHad he done so, things may\nhave been different. There is a\nteacher shortage, you know.\nAbe Also Wondered About\nReverence For Law\nThere is something of ill-omen\namongst us the increasing\ndisregard for law which pervades\nthe country; Accounts of out\nrages committed by mobs, from\nthe every-day news of the times\nHow shall we fortify against\nit? Let reverence for the laws,\nbe breathed by every American\nmother, to -the lisping babe, that\nprattles on her lap let it be\ntaught in schools and in col\nleges; let it be written in Prim\nmers, spelling books, and in Al\nmanacs; let it be preached from\nthe pulpit, proclaimed in legisla\ntive halls, and enforced in courts\nof justice.\nABRAHAM LINCOLN\nTactics Be Damned!\u2014\n\"When's That There Bushwhacker?\"\nRecently the distinguished col\numnist of the Louisville Times,\nMr. B. M. Atkinson, Jr., praised\nthe sound thinking and military\ntactics of Matt Dillion, U. S.\nMarshal.\nWhile Mr. Atkinson is a reco\ngnized authority on television,\nhaving so much leisure time to\nwatch after dashing off his daily\ncolumn in 20 or 30 minutes be\ntween coffee breaks, we must en\nter a demurrer.\nOn a recent Saturday night\nMatt Dillion, U. S. Marshal, was\napparently being led into an am\nbush by a wide-eyed blonde,\ntastefully attired for the rough\nfrontier life in a get-up straight\nout of Bergdorf-Goodman.. Just\nwhen we were beginning to\nsquirm on the sofa, thinking any\nminute a bullet would have us\nlooking forward to next week\u2019s\nepisode of Chester Whatshisname,\nU. S. Marshall, wise old Matt\nreined up.\n\u201cJenny,\u201d he said, \"he\u2019s down\nthere waiting for me, isn\u2019t he?\u201d\nCowed by Matt\u2019s steely gaze.\nJenny confessed. (Yes, her ac\ncomplice was waiting down there\nin the river bottom to knock off\nTV\u2019s No. 1 gunslinger, legal divi\nsion.\n\u201cOkay,\u201d said Matt, \u201cwait here.\u201d\nHe immediately climbed back\non his horse, who incidentally is\nthe greatest weight carrier since\nDiscovery, and rode right down\nto the river bottom.\nThe villian was hiding behind\na tree, armed with a rifle.\nDillon was on horseback.\nSpurning use of his own rifle,\nMat fought with a revolver.\nThere was a brief exchange,\nand dead in the mud of the river\nbottom was the bushwacking\nscoundrel. Matt never got a\nscratch.\nMr. Atkinson, take the stand.\nWhat kind of a triple-plated idiot\nis your hero? Doesn\u2019t he know\none man behind a tree with a rifle\nfigures to kill a dozen halfwits\nwho try to hit him with pistol\nfire from horseback?\n(The Kentucky Irish-American)\nbnort Keporr un\u2014\nThe Sputnik Sport\nWhatever else the Sputniks\nhave done they have produced an\nunending crop of funny stories\ninside Russia.\nThere is the obvious one that\nthe second satellite was, of course,\nsent up by the security services\nto keep a watch on what the first\nwas up to.\nThere is the other story that\ncrowds in Albania suddenly be\ngan demonstrating for joy. They\nhad heard the rumour that Russia\nwas to \u2018let loose a satellite in\nouter space\u2019 and had jumped to\nthe conclusion that their own dis\ntant Albania was to be freed.\n(The Times, of London)","height":"21594","width":"14460"}}
